title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.3: RURAL Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH)

description.narrative: By 2020 people living in 5 target districts have access to improved water and sanitation services and are practicing safe hygiene behaviours (Target - 15,000 rural people with access to water, 90,000 with access to sanitation and 15 Health Posts with WASH facilities), which contributes to Hygiene, Sanitation, Sanitation (Covid), Wash And Emergencies, Water, Water Supply. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, reduced child mortality and under-nutrition through improved and equitable use of high impact health, nutrition and WASH interventions.

title.narrative: By 2020 people living in 5 target districts have access to improved water and sanitation services and are practicing safe hygienebehaviours (Target - 15,000 rural people with access to water, 90,000 with access to sanitation and 15 Health Posts with WASHfacilities)

description.narrative: Overall, there has been good progress in the implementation of the WASH program. In 2020, UNICEF’s direct WASH interventions in communities and institutions have given 80,417 persons access to improved water, sanitation and hygiene services in all the 13 municipalities in Timor-Leste improving the standard of life and resilience against COVID19 and natural disasters while 44 communities (sub villages) became open defecation free. The WASH program has been boosted by the COVID-19 response interventions, especially the promotion of handwashing with soap and clean water. However, the availability of water remains a key challenge. | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:03/02/2021
